post_text:
We have been made aware of Instagram accounts that appear to be DPS affiliated but are not. Please note that these accounts are not official Denver Public Schools accounts.

To get help, you can report your concerns through the DPS’ Discrimination Prevention and Response and Title IX team by email at reportdiscrimination@dpsk12.org or by phone at 720-423-3517. You can reach out to your building level social worker, school psychologist or counselor for support.

You can also utilize the Safe2Tell number or send a text to anonymously report an incident to 1-877-542-7233 or at safe2tell.org. This will allow officials to follow up on your concern. The National Sexual Assault Hotline (1-800-656-4673) is another important resources that provide confidential service 24/7.

For more information, you can visit our website below.

post_text:
The African American Young Ladies Summit (@AAYLS) is welcoming new members! If you are a Black/African American young lady between 6th - 12 grade, join AAYLS to become equipped with the tools you’ll need for a lifelong journey of personal success and achievement. Through a community of supportive adults and peers, students will build knowledge of topics including: academic scholarships, leadership, self worth and confidence, belonging and connectedness, community engagement, financial stability, Afro-beauty and overcoming racial barriers in society, school and life.

Students in the program have commented “I love to be in a place where I see myself in others” and “I learned that we are better together.”

The next AAYLS event, Sista 2 Sista, is scheduled for September 26th. To register for this virtual event, please visit ⬇️

post_text: We are excited to announce that DPS will be providing free breakfast and lunch meals to all kids 18 years old and younger through December 31. Families can pick up breakfast and lunch meals Monday through Friday from 11 a.m. until 1 p.m. at school and community sites throughout the city. Students do not need to be present for adults to pick up their meals, and families can visit any school site regardless of which school they attend. Breakfast and lunch meals for adults are also available for purchase at a small cost. More information ⬇️

We know that COVID-19 has brought new and unique challenges for our families, so we’ve been working with the community to support. Thanks to the Denver Public Schools Family and Community Engagement (FACE) team, DPS has helped:

• Provide 28 schools with over 2,000 masks through a donation drive from partners such as the Denver Public Library Employee Volunteers and D.A. Davidson & Co.
• Distribute $100,000 to families who did not receive stimulus support in March, thanks to the FACE Centers completing 100 referrals for the Left Behind Workers Fund in collaboration Impact Charitable. Direct cash payments allowed those without work to pay their rent, buy groceries and provide for their families.

Learn more ⬇️

post_text: The DPS Board of Education voted on Thursday to adopt a bond and mill levy proposal for the November 2020 ballot. Denver voters will be asked to consider two measures: a $795 million bond that would provide funding to build and maintain schools, and a $32 million Debt Free Schools Ballot Initiative that would provide operating dollars to fund priorities such as mental health, nursing, and special education supports. Learn more ⬇️
shared_text:
DPSK12.ORG
DPS Board of Education Moves to Ask Voters to Approve Bond and Mill Levy in November | Denver Public Schools
text:
The DPS Board of Education voted on Thursday to adopt a bond and mill levy proposal for the November 2020 ballot. Denver voters will be asked to consider two measures: a $795 million bond that would provide funding to build and maintain schools, and a $32 million Debt Free Schools Ballot Initiative that would provide operating dollars to fund priorities such as mental health, nursing, and special education supports. Learn more ⬇️

DPSK12.ORG
DPS Board of Education Moves to Ask Voters to Approve Bond and Mill Levy in November | Denver Public Schools

Join us in congratulating Marianna Lucero of Goldrick Elementary, recipient of the Colorado Thespians Elementary Educator of the Year Award!

In addition to being an elementary theater and dance teacher, she is a company actor for Su Teatro, #Denver’s first and only Chicanx Theatre Company.

She has also led student work that centers around cultural inclusivity, building social awareness, and advocating for positive social change in the communities of color.

post_text:
FAQ UPDATE: We know that our families, teachers and staff members need clear answers on what to expect for this school year. We are working closely with our health experts to define parameters around what a safe reopening looks like so that our students can return to face-to-face instruction in our school buildings. We also are building protocols for what transitioning between our learning scenarios will look like as well as in-depth contingency plans in the event that there is a COVID outbreak and students need to return to remote classrooms again. These decisions will be based on the best available modeling data on COVID-19 conditions, with guidance from our local and state partners.

For now, we thank you for your patience and for helping us build a plan that prioritizes safety and is responsive to the needs of our community. We will continue to update the FAQ below as our workgroups finalize details.

DPSK12.ORG

We also are building protocols for what transitioning between our learning scenarios will look like as well as in-depth contingency plans in the event that there is a COVID outbreak and students need to return to remote classrooms again. These decisions will be based on the best available modeling data on COVID-19 conditions, with guidance from our local and state partners.

ANNOUNCEMENT & SURVEY: Based on updated health guidance, we are planning for all DPS students to be able to attend school this fall in-person and full-time, with strong health precautions in place to keep our students and staff safe during the ongoing pandemic.

The current plan is to have schools open at full strength in August, offering full-time, in-person instruction. There will also be an option for fully online learning for families who want it. Families who choose this option will not lose their seat at their current school.

To help us plan for both enrollment and bus-transportation needs, we ask that you please fill out this survey by July 10.

We’re continuing our close partnership with Denver Health/DDPHE, and will keep parents updated every step of the way.

post_text:
155 years ago on June 19, African Americans living in Texas and across the west learned of their freedom – two years after the signing of the Emancipation Proclamation. Juneteenth is a celebration of this day, recognizing the end of slavery and the beginning of African American independence in the United States. In preparation for tomorrow's celebration, join us by:
• Taking a virtual tour of the Slavery and Freedom exhibit at the National Museum of African American History and Culture ⬇️
• Tuning into the Virtual Juneteenth music festival: juneteenthmusicfestival.com

post_text:
This weekend, DPS students organized and led a Black Lives Matter demonstration, which honored George Floyd and emphasized the need for more Black educators in schools.

The Colorado Sun detailed the event, which for many of these students was the culmination of a lifetime of challenge:

“For all the grief and heartache expressed over those lives, the throngs of young people also marched forward on a hopeful note. On Sunday, they waved their signs left to right in unison while music blared, they competed in quick dance competitions along East Colfax Avenue and people of many races banned together in pursuit of change.”
shared_text:
COLORADOSUN.COM
Tragedy has prepared Colorado students for their next battle: police brutality and racism

The Denver Public Schools Board of Education and Superintendent would like to take a moment to reflect on the tragic death of George Floyd. Floyd, 46, died Monday in Minneapolis. He spent his final moments pleading for his life as an officer held him down, pinning him to the ground with his knee. His last words were “I can’t breathe.” Floyd’s pleas are ignored. His eyes shut, the pleading stops, and he is pronounced dead shortly after.

Read the full statement below.

Because of the COVID-19 health crisis, Denver Public Schools has developed plans for what in-person learning may look like once we are able to safely welcome students back into our buildings.

The discussions on what this could look like have been extensive, with guidance from Denver Public Health and the Denver Department of Public Health and Environment, as well as with feedback from our students, families, teachers, and school leaders.

This video gives a glimpse at what our new learning environments may look like.

For more information in English & Spanish: https://www.dpsk12.org/planning-for-a-safe-return-to-school/

post_text:
SOLICITUD PARA RECABAR LOS COMENTARIOS DE LA COMUNIDAD: debido a la recesión económica provocada por la pandemia de COVID-19, DPS debe prepararse para una reducción considerable del financiamiento para el año escolar 2020-21. Con el fin de apoyar el proceso para el desarrollo presupuestario del año escolar 2020-21, el Consejo de Educación de DPS convoca la creación de un Comité Asesor Presupuestario (BAC, por su sigla en inglés).

El BAC estará formado por tres integrantes de la comunidad: un estudiante, un joven exalumno de DPS y un padre. A fin de garantizar la familiaridad con el proceso presupuestario de DPS, las personas que sean seleccionadas deberán servir (o haber servido en forma reciente) en algún comité actual de DPS.

Llene la solicitud para formar parte del BAC, a más tardar el mediodía del jueves, 30 de abril ⬇️

post_text:
REQUEST FOR COMMUNITY INPUT: With the economic downturn that has resulted from the COVID-19 pandemic, DPS must prepare for a significant reduction in funding (bit.ly/3by3x21) for the 2020-21 school year. To support the budget development process for the 2020-21 school year, the DPS Board of Education is convening a Budget Advisory Committee (BAC).

The BAC will have three community members: one student, one young DPS alumni and one parent. In order to ensure familiarity with the DPS budget process, members will be selected from individuals who are serving on (or have recently served on) existing DPS committees.

Fill out the BAC application by noon on Thursday, April 30 ⬇️

This Friday is GLSEN's National #DayofSilence, a student-led event where folks take a vow of silence to highlight the silencing and erasure of LGBTQ+ people at school. Learn more about ways to participate in the Day of Silence virtually ⬇️

post_text: DPS leadership has made the decision to remain with remote learning for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. This means that all DPS schools will remain closed to in-person classes for the remainder of the school year.
text: DPS leadership has made the decision to remain with remote learning for the rest of the 2019-20 school year. This means that all DPS schools will remain closed to in-person classes for the remainder of the school year.

post_text:
If your high school student still needs a computer, you can pick one up on Tuesday, April 7 or Wednesday, April 8 between 10:30 a.m. and 1 p.m. at one of the 12 DPS schools that we’re using for technology distribution.

At this time, we are distributing computers to high school students only, as well as students who attend 6-12 schools.
